 class="main-svg" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="538.3333333333334" height="333.33333333333337"><g class="hoverlayer"></g></svg></div></div></div></foreignObject></g><text class="draggable" name="text" x="55" y="150" r="0" rtemp="0" transform="rotate(0 55 150)" style="fill: rgb(224, 41, 59); font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-size: 12px; font-family: bolder;">V(in)</text><text class="draggable" name="text" x="209" y="173" r="0" rtemp="0" transform="rotate(0 209 173)" style="fill: rgb(0, 42, 255); font-weight: bolder; font-style: normal; font-size: 12px; font-family: bold;">V(out)</text><g transform="translate(408,15)" x="408" y="15" title="codeHTML" width="523" height="546" class="codeHTML" name="codeHTML" rot="0"><foreignObject x="0" y="0" width="222" height="200" style="height: 546px; width: 871.667px;"><div name="htmlCode" style="zoom: 60%; height: 546px; width: 871.667px;" code="<div class=&quot;ch&quot;>
    
    <h1>CMOS Inverter - SPICE Time Domain Analysis</h1>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot;>
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>M1:</strong> PMOS Transistor (pull-up network)</li>
            <li><strong>M2:</strong> NMOS Transistor (pull-down network)</li>
            <li><strong>V1:</strong> DC Power Supply = 5V</li>
            <li><strong>VDD (Input):</strong> Pulse Source PULSE(0 5 0 1n 1n 10n 20n)</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> V(out) at the common drain node</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Input Signal Parameters</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        PULSE(Vlow Vhigh Tdelay Trise Tfall Tpulse Tperiod)<br>
        PULSE(0 5 0 1ns 1ns 10ns 20ns)<br>
        Frequency = 1/Tperiod = 1/20ns = <strong>50 MHz</strong>
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-grid&quot;>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col blue&quot;>
            <h3>Input Signal V(in) - Red</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Square wave oscillating between 0V and 5V</li>
                <li>Period = 20 ns (50 MHz frequency)</li>
                <li>Duty cycle = 50% (10ns HIGH, 10ns LOW)</li>
                <li>Rise and fall times = 1 ns</li>
                <li>Acts as the digital input stimulus</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col red&quot;>
            <h3>Output Signal V(out) - Blue</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Inverted version of the input signal</li>
                <li>When V(in) = 5V (HIGH) → V(out) = 0V (LOW)</li>
                <li>When V(in) = 0V (LOW) → V(out) = 5V (HIGH)</li>
                <li>Full rail-to-rail swing (0V to 5V)</li>
                <li>180° phase shift relative to input</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card green-border&quot;>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>This circuit is a <strong>CMOS Inverter</strong>, the fundamental building block of digital logic. When the input is LOW, the PMOS (M1) turns ON and pulls the output to VDD (5V). When the input is HIGH, the NMOS (M2) turns ON and pulls the output to GND (0V). The complementary operation of the two transistors ensures that only one transistor conducts at a time, resulting in <strong>very low static power consumption</strong>. The output perfectly inverts the input with full voltage swing, demonstrating ideal digital inverter behavior at 50 MHz.</p>
    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot; style=&quot;background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;&quot;>
        <h2 style=&quot;color: #16a085;&quot;>CMOS Inverter Characteristics</h2>
        <ul style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>
            <li><strong>Logic Function:</strong> NOT gate (Y = )</li>
            <li><strong>Power Consumption:</strong> Near zero in static state (no DC path from VDD to GND)</li>
            <li><strong>Noise Margin:</strong> High noise immunity due to rail-to-rail output</li>
            <li><strong>Switching:</strong> Dynamic power consumed only during transitions</li>
            <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Foundation of all CMOS digital ICs (processors, memory, logic gates)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div>"><div class="ch">
    
    <h1>CMOS Inverter - SPICE Time Domain Analysis</h1>

    <div class="ch-card">
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>M1:</strong> PMOS Transistor (pull-up network)</li>
            <li><strong>M2:</strong> NMOS Transistor (pull-down network)</li>
            <li><strong>V1:</strong> DC Power Supply = 5V</li>
            <li><strong>VDD (Input):</strong> Pulse Source PULSE(0 5 0 1n 1n 10n 20n)</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> V(out) at the common drain node</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Input Signal Parameters</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        PULSE(Vlow Vhigh Tdelay Trise Tfall Tpulse Tperiod)<br>
        PULSE(0 5 0 1ns 1ns 10ns 20ns)<br>
        Frequency = 1/Tperiod = 1/20ns = <strong>50 MHz</strong>
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class="ch-grid">

        <div class="ch-col blue">
            <h3>Input Signal V(in) - Red</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Square wave oscillating between 0V and 5V</li>
                <li>Period = 20 ns (50 MHz frequency)</li>
                <li>Duty cycle = 50% (10ns HIGH, 10ns LOW)</li>
                <li>Rise and fall times = 1 ns</li>
                <li>Acts as the digital input stimulus</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="ch-col red">
            <h3>Output Signal V(out) - Blue</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Inverted version of the input signal</li>
                <li>When V(in) = 5V (HIGH) → V(out) = 0V (LOW)</li>
                <li>When V(in) = 0V (LOW) → V(out) = 5V (HIGH)</li>
                <li>Full rail-to-rail swing (0V to 5V)</li>
                <li>180° phase shift relative to input</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="ch-card green-border">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">This circuit is a <strong>CMOS Inverter</strong>, the fundamental building block of digital logic. When the input is LOW, the PMOS (M1) turns ON and pulls the output to VDD (5V). When the input is HIGH, the NMOS (M2) turns ON and pulls the output to GND (0V). The complementary operation of the two transistors ensures that only one transistor conducts at a time, resulting in <strong>very low static power consumption</strong>. The output perfectly inverts the input with full voltage swing, demonstrating ideal digital inverter behavior at 50 MHz.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ch-card" style="background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;">
        <h2 style="color: #16a085;">CMOS Inverter Characteristics</h2>
        <ul style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
            <li><strong>Logic Function:</strong> NOT gate (Y = )</li>
            <li><strong>Power Consumption:</strong> Near zero in static state (no DC path from VDD to GND)</li>
            <li><strong>Noise Margin:</strong> High noise immunity due to rail-to-rail output</li>
            <li><strong>Switching:</strong> Dynamic power consumed only during transitions</li>
            <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Foundation of all CMOS digital ICs (processors, memory, logic gates)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div></div></foreignObject></g>